#load "c_load/Library";
/*
The chord_s3 (3-dimension chord space) is a per-octave repeating space for 3-note chords.
Traditionally a piano (or midi roll) contains all possible unordered 1-note sets in each octave.
Similarly, a chord_s3 contains all possible unordered 3-note sets in each octave.
We then apply this idea to any dimension.
All dimensions higher than 3 are mapped onto the 3 dimensional visual plane.

It is recommended to read through the code and think about it.
Feelings should also be recognized and acknowledged.

"ctrl+alt+d" for debug mode.
"ctrl+alt+c" to compile.
"F5" to run the code.
Put "open_op cs3" in the terminal and press "Enter"
to see the chord_s3 in the 3d op space.

This space was created/discovered by Dimitri Tymoczko.
"Mathematicians would describe our quotient space as “the n-torus modulo the symmetric group that acts
on n elements”—symbolically, Tn/Sn. Here, Tn is the mathematical symbol for the
n-torus, the space of ordered pitch-class sequences; Sn refers to the collection of oper-
ations that reorder n elements; and the division symbol instructs us to glue together
points related by the operations that follow. Thus the mathematical symbol “Tn/Sn”
means “the space that results when you start with ordered pitch-class sequences and
disregard order.”" - Dimitry Tymoczko

Developer Remarks :
At 6+ dimensions with the ALL filter, the program will crash due to lack of rendering memory.
This is done intentionally to keep each op space at < 5Mb of memory.
A filter is recommended to be used for 6+ dimensions.
If requested, a runtime setting can be added to adjust the rendering memory size.
At 5+ dimensions the program will halt momentarily while generating.
On the developer's machine, the 5d space takes around 0.3 seconds to generate.
The 6d space takes around 7 seconds to generate.
The 7d space takes over 2 minutes to generate.
At 4+ dimensions, the ALL space tends to be somewhat incomprehensible.
Filters are generally recommended.
It is the developer's opinion that exploring this space is best done
through custom code written by you for your particular use case through a dynamic library.
This will be added by request but currently requires a private compiler to do so.
For more information, please ask on discord.
*/
main :: () {
	csd : AsmOpSpaceData;
	csd.op_space_type = AsmOpSpaceType.space_3d;
	csd.op_space_name = "cs3";
	#asm{ get_or_create_op_space csd; }
	clear : AsmClearOpData;
	clear.op_space_id = csd.ret_op_space_id;
	#asm{ clear_op_space clear; }

	//"WASD" and "IJKL" can be used to move around the 3d space.
	cs3 : AsmSpace3Data;
	cs3.op_space_id = csd.ret_op_space_id;
	cs3.tuning_system_id = 0;
	cs3.higher_dim = 3;
	cs3.s3_cam_start_type = S3CamStartType.USER_SET;
	// cs3.cam_start_pos = Vector3.{0.,0.,0.};
	cs3.osc_wave_type = OscWaveType.SINE;
	cs3.set_3d_perspective = false;
	cs3.depth = 24.0;
	cs3.n = 1.0; 
	cs3.f = 240.0;
	csf_array : [1] AsmCSFilter;
	csf_array[0].filter_type = ChordSpaceFilterType.ALL;
	//csf_array[0].filter_type = ChordSpaceFilterType.CHROMATIC;
	//"O" and "U" can be used to dynamically change the sum value of the SUM filter.
	//csf_array[0].filter_type = ChordSpaceFilterType.SUM;
	cs3.asm_cs_filters = csf_array;
	#asm{ create_cs3 cs3; }

	mc : MapChordS3Data;
	mc.op_space_id = cs3.op_space_id;
	mc.vl_start_chord = float.[0,4,7];
	mc.vl_deltas = float.[
		0,-1,0,
		8,9,8
	];
	#asm{ map_cs3 mc; }
}